[1] Nigeria
Date: 12 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information, Vol. 19, No. 6. [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_32.HTM#Sec2>

Avian Influenza In Nigeria
-------------------------------
(Disease never reported before in Nigeria in its highly pathogenic form).
Immediate notification report.
Information received on 6 and 8 Feb 2006 from Dr. Junaidu A. Maina,
Acting Director, Department of Livestock and Pest Control Services,
Federal Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development, Abuja:
Report date: 8 Feb 2006.
Reason for immediate notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease
or infection in a country or zone/compartment.
Identification of agent: highly pathogenic avian influenza virus subtype H5N1.
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 6 Feb 2006.
Date of start of the event: 10 Jan 2006.
Clinical disease: yes.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, post-mortem and laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
1st administrative division (State): Kaduna
Lower administrative division (Local Government Area): Igabi
Type of epidemiological unit: farm
Name of the location: Jaji
Latitude: 10o 47.34
Longitude: N7o 32.188 E
Date of start of the outbreak: 10 Jan 2006
Species: avi
Number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
46 000 / 42 000 / 40 000 / -- / 0
Description of affected population: a commercial poultry layer
production unit with poultry kept in battery cages. The farm has a
mixture of different breeds of birds sourced from different places
within the country. Some ostriches are also kept at the farm.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: National Veterinary
Research Institute, Vom, Nigeria
Species examined: poultry
Diagnostic tests used: agar-gel immunodiffusion test; virus isolation.
Date: 6 Feb 2006
Results: positive
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: OIE Reference
Laboratory for avian influenza and Newcastle disease, Padova, Italy
Species examined: poultry
Diagnostic tests used: 1. Real-time PCR(1).
Results: 1. Positive for influenza virus type A.
Diagnostic tests used: 2. Hemagglutination inhibition and
neuraminidase inhibition tests.
Results: 2. Positive for avian influenza virus subtype H5N1.
Diagnostic tests used: 3. PCR(1) for the H5 gene.
Results: 3. Positive for H5.
Diagnostic tests used: 4. Sequence analysis.
Results: 4. Amino acid sequence at cleavage site reveals a highly
pathogenic avian influenza profile.
Date: 7 Feb 2006
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive.
Control measures
A. Undertaken:
- stamping out;
- quarantine;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment.
B. To be undertaken:
- movement control inside the country.
Since the confirmation of the presence of the disease, the emergency
plan against the disease has been activated.
Detailed epidemiological investigations are being carried out all
over the country to determine the source of the infection and prevent
its spread.
Treatment of affected animals: yes (birds were treated by the owner
with broad-spectrum antibiotics before confirmation of infection).
Vaccination prohibited: yes.
Final report: no.
(1) PCR: polymerase chain reaction
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The mortality rate of 42 000/46 000 (91.3 percent) and case fatality
rate of 40 000/42 000 (95.2 percent) are very high. ProMED-mail has
learned that the approximately 80 ostriches on the farm have been
depopulated. - Mod.PC]
